{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17651072","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17651072"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:19:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:19:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18427"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18427","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18427"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11145"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114217"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11145","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11145"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18427"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96217"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"10266"},{"type":"tags","id":"10275"},{"type":"tags","id":"10276"},{"type":"tags","id":"10278"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25828"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25832"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114217","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114217"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following describes the primary characteristic of slow muscle fibres?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oxidative","Glycolytic","Anaerobic","Fast-twitch","Low myoglobin content"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ESlow muscle fibres, also known as type I fibres, are primarily \u003Cstrong\u003Eoxidative\u003C/strong\u003E. They are adapted for endurance activities and are characterised by a high density of mitochondria and myoglobin, which support aerobic metabolism. This allows them to sustain prolonged activity without fatigue.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlycolytic\u003C/strong\u003E fibres, or type II fibres, are fast-twitch fibres that rely on anaerobic metabolism for quick bursts of power and speed, but they fatigue more quickly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnaerobic\u003C/strong\u003E metabolism is more characteristic of fast-twitch fibres, which are not the primary fibres used in endurance activities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFast-twitch\u003C/strong\u003E fibres are not the primary fibres used in endurance activities; they are more suited for short, explosive movements.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESlow muscle fibres have a \u003Cstrong\u003Ehigh myoglobin content\u003C/strong\u003E, which is essential for their oxidative capacity, not low as suggested in the incorrect option.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Slow muscle fibres, also known as type I fibres, are primarily oxidative and are adapted for endurance activities.","These fibres have a high density of mitochondria and myoglobin, which support aerobic metabolism."],"references":["Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2021. Chapter 6; pg. 88","Patton, K. T., \u0026 Thibodeau, G. A. (2018). Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book: Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","Longo, U. G., \u0026 Denaro, V. (Eds.). (2023). Textbook of musculoskeletal disorders. Springer Nature","Hughes, S. H. (2022). The Musculoskeletal System: The Musculoskeletal System-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"